00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:41.360
This is a screen shot from my
TED talk from a few weeks ago

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:44.000
in which I really talked
about the global connectivity

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.340
revolution, which is also
the thesis of the book.

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:49.490
It's effectively saying
that all of the maps that

00:05:49.490 --> 00:05:51.100
hang on your walls
and our walls,

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:54.030
I accuse them all
of being completely

00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:57.070
wrong and biased and
misleading because they always

00:05:57.070 --> 00:06:00.430
show us the political
boundaries as the primary lines.

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:04.370
They tend to ignore completely
infrastructural lines.

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:06.860
And yet, the irony
being that we have

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:10.840
150 times more mileage
of infrastructure than we

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:12.950
have mileage of borders.

00:06:12.950 --> 00:06:16.070
We have less than
500,000 kilometers

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:18.210
of borders between
countries, and we

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:21.880
have something on the order
of 75 million kilometers

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:24.850
worth of what you
see here, which

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:30.300
is highways and railways-- so
transportation-- oil and gas

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:32.240
pipelines and
electricity grids-- which

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:36.140
is energy-- and of
course, internet cables--

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:36.950
communications.

00:06:36.950 --> 00:06:38.350
And that's just the beginning.

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.290
This revolution that I'm
talking about already

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:44.901
utterly overwhelms in terms
of how it unfolds itself

00:06:44.901 --> 00:06:45.900
on the map of the world.

00:06:45.900 --> 00:06:49.240
It actually totally overwhelms
our political divisions.

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:52.250
And yet, we're just
in the early phases

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:55.900
of building out the planet
through these transportation,

00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:57.650
energy, and communications
infrastructure.

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:02.110
So I like to cite Autodesk-- the
design engineering firm-- that

00:07:02.110 --> 00:07:05.100
says that we'll build more
infrastructure in the next 40

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:08.260
years than we have in
the last 4,000 years.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.130
So this revolution
is just underway.

00:07:10.130 --> 00:07:12.150
The spending that we're
going to put into this

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:15.290
amounts already to $4 or
$5 trillion dollars a year,

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:20.040
which is double what we spend
on all the military and defense

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:21.540
establishments in the world.

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:23.600
So I think that this
is the beginning

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:26.370
of a great shift in the world.

00:07:26.370 --> 00:07:28.370
And I want to set out to map it.

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:31.050
And I believe that it
requires, if you really

00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:35.220
take this infrastructural
development

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:36.960
to its logical
conclusion, you literally

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:40.610
have to re-imagine how life is
organized on the planet Earth.

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:43.880
We always think of ourselves--
we're raised and trained--

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:46.149
in this epoc since
the 17th century,

00:07:46.149 --> 00:07:48.690
basically, to think of ourselves
as being organized according

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:49.590
to countries.

00:07:49.590 --> 00:07:52.910
Who you are is where you are and
where you are is in a country.

00:07:52.910 --> 00:07:56.480
And your identity, therefore,
is that national identity.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:58.880
And I really want to push
the envelope here and say

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:01.730
that, in fact, we are
organized much more according

00:08:01.730 --> 00:08:04.780
to our infrastructure and our
supply chains and our cities.

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:07.100
So instead of
nations and borders,

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:09.450
we live in a world of
infrastructures, cities,

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:10.320
and supply chains.

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:13.470
And those matter and
shape who you are,

00:08:13.470 --> 00:08:16.920
what you are, what you do,
and your potential outcomes

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:20.580
in life way more than just
what your national identity is.

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:23.040
And that contradicts
the oldest adage

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:26.090
that we know that all children
learn in school, which

00:08:26.090 --> 00:08:28.340
is that geography is destiny.

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:29.830
And I'm arguing that's not true.

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:32.570
I'm arguing that connectivity
has now become destiny.

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:34.400
Connectivity is a lifeline.

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:36.780
It's an opportunity.

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:40.210
And it also creates multiple
sources and possibilities

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:42.220
for your identity in
ways that we're just

00:08:42.220 --> 00:08:44.214
starting to appreciate today.

00:08:44.214 --> 00:08:45.630
And this infrastructure,
what's so

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:48.110
fascinating from an
engineering standpoint,

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.420
there's a term that's
little used that I think

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:52.500
is going to become more
prominent these days,

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:54.320
and its topographical
engineering.

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:57.334
And so I actually open the book
with a travel around the world.

00:08:57.334 --> 00:08:59.500
Imagine that you could
travel around the whole world

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:01.000
without leaving the ground.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.640
You can do so through all
of the new railways and very

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:07.440
large floating
structures-- there's

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:10.580
an acronym, VLFS, in the field
of oil and gas engineering.

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:12.030
We're building
these floating oil

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:15.590
rigs that are larger than
the Sydney Opera House.

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:18.150
Even cruise ships
that size, we're

00:09:18.150 --> 00:09:20.390
infrastructure able
to modify the earth.

00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:22.810
So you're familiar with
this term anthropocene--

00:09:22.810 --> 00:09:27.070
this age in which mankind's
impact on the ecology

00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:28.980
on the planet become
so systemic that it

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:32.387
changes the nature of
the global environment.

00:09:32.387 --> 00:09:33.470
And how have we done that?

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:36.640
We've done it through
this incredible revolution

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:39.860
in our durable
engineering capability.

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:42.680
So we're physically
constructing and reconstructing

00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:46.310
and modifying the earth through
all this infrastructure.

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:50.180
And all of those infrastructures
are so much more durable

00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:52.730
than our nations and
states and boundaries.

00:09:52.730 --> 00:09:56.017
As I point out
repeatedly, we've had

00:09:56.017 --> 00:09:57.600
cities-- cities are
the infrastructure

00:09:57.600 --> 00:10:00.280
that you can see from space.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:02.510
You can't see countries
and borders from space.

00:10:02.510 --> 00:10:03.480
You can see cities.

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:05.440
You can even see railways now.

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:07.150
You can see tall buildings.

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:10.460
You can see all sorts
of man-made things.

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:12.330
You can't really see borders.

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:14.386
They're actually
much more artificial

00:10:14.386 --> 00:10:16.010
than the infrastructures
that we build.

00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:18.810
And cities outlast every
empire in every country that

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:20.400
nominally governs them, right?

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:22.290
We have had cities
for 5,000 years.

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:23.110
We've had Baghdad.

00:10:23.110 --> 00:10:25.740
We've had a Constantinople--
now Istanbul.

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:29.450
And we've had Beirut and
Alexandria and so forth.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:32.110
The countries that
seem like they

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:34.650
are the bedrock of our
international system,

00:10:34.650 --> 00:10:38.150
legally, are actually fairly
insignificant in comparison

00:10:38.150 --> 00:10:40.326
to the long histories
of our cities have.

00:10:40.326 --> 00:10:42.200
And now the connectivity
between those cities

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:44.460
is becoming so robust
that we are becoming

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:48.140
what I call "a global network
civilization"-- not a world

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:50.530
in which states and the
relations among them

00:10:50.530 --> 00:10:53.251
actually operate the system.

00:10:53.251 --> 00:10:55.750
It may seem like that if you
look at an organizational chart

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:56.344
of the UN.

00:10:56.344 --> 00:10:59.010
But because you're looking at an
organizational chart of the UN,

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:00.801
you think that that is
how the world works.

00:11:00.801 --> 00:11:04.990
If you look at the world
itself, from the outside,

00:11:04.990 --> 00:11:09.200
you would be seeing this.

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:10.710
This is the real world.

00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:12.730
This is how the
world actually works,

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:15.440
not the way institutions
are structured.

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:16.830
And this is truly global.

00:11:16.830 --> 00:11:19.410
We've never lived in a
world where world trade is

00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:22.740
so all-encompassing and
where all the continents are

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:26.230
included in that system
on relatively equal terms.

00:11:26.230 --> 00:11:28.680
You could have, obviously--
in the colonial era,

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:32.030
you had the dominance
over the developing

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:33.530
countries in the
southern hemisphere

00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:36.756
by a few European empires.

00:11:36.756 --> 00:11:37.880
Today, you don't have that.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:43.200
Today, you have these growing,
dense continental economic

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:45.230
systems that are
increasingly tied

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:48.020
to each other by infrastructure
and by supply chains.

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:50.200
The same thing is happening
in capital markets.

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:52.640
So what it means is that this
world of nations and borders

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:56.487
is much more one that I
call a supply chain world.

00:11:56.487 --> 00:11:58.070
And it's a world
that some described--

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:01.780
the physicist, Michio Kaku,
calls it perfect capitalism.

00:12:01.780 --> 00:12:04.130
In a world where everything
is totally connected,

00:12:04.130 --> 00:12:07.160
you unite all of these
historical forces

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:09.450
that economists and
sociologists have been talking

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:10.730
about for hundreds of years.

00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:13.800
You bring together Adam Smith's
free markets, David Ricardo's

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:16.090
comparative advantage, and
Emile Durkheim's division

00:12:16.090 --> 00:12:18.060
of labor-- Durkheim
is my favorite.

00:12:18.060 --> 00:12:20.580
Ricardo Haussmann
from Harvard who

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:23.350
talks about a complexity
of production.

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:26.610
And you can achieve what
economics is really all about,

00:12:26.610 --> 00:12:29.306
which is the optimization
of land, labor, capital,

00:12:29.306 --> 00:12:29.930
and production.

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:31.630
And of course, you
do so in a way that

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:36.100
isn't organized according to
territorial political units,

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:38.730
but anywhere where you
want to produce something,

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:41.720
you can do so.

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:44.174
So like I said, I want to get
more into some of the maps,

00:12:44.174 --> 00:12:46.090
and I want to talk about
what the supply chain

00:12:46.090 --> 00:12:47.862
world of total
connectivity looks like.

00:12:47.862 --> 00:12:49.320
Well, it's a world
in fact where we

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:51.990
have very substantial
mobility of people.

00:12:51.990 --> 00:12:55.040
Globalization-- and this is
a book about globalization--

00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:56.640
is ultimately all about people.

00:12:56.640 --> 00:12:58.310
The history of
globalization begins

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:01.970
with mankind's wanderings out
of the African continent 60,000

00:13:01.970 --> 00:13:04.540
some years ago, and it
hasn't stopped, obviously.

00:13:04.540 --> 00:13:07.030
It continues unabated.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:08.750
So today's headlines
are dominated

00:13:08.750 --> 00:13:10.590
by Donald Trump
wanting to put up

00:13:10.590 --> 00:13:14.800
a wall or European
populist politicians

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:17.020
talking about wanting
to close borders.

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:19.870
But the fact is that
that is a reaction

00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:24.080
to the enormous amounts of
migration that have taken place

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:25.350
and continue to take place.

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:28.429
That is not the reality
of closing borders

00:13:28.429 --> 00:13:30.470
or of pushing migrants
back because that actually

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:31.510
hasn't happened.

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:35.370
Europe let in one million
migrants in the year 2015,

00:13:35.370 --> 00:13:36.830
more than ever before.

00:13:36.830 --> 00:13:38.380
So that's talk.

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:41.210
The reality is this enormous
expansion of migration,

00:13:41.210 --> 00:13:43.610
such that there
are 230, 250, some

00:13:43.610 --> 00:13:46.680
say 300 million people
today living outside

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:48.550
of their country of origin.

00:13:48.550 --> 00:13:50.290
They might be even
permanent expats.

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:52.750
And little do many
people in America

00:13:52.750 --> 00:13:55.200
realize that there are more
American expats than ever

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:56.000
before.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.360
Nine million Americans who
live outside the United States.

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:03.100
That's more than double what
the normal, standard amount

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:05.960
has been over the
last 10, 15 years.

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:06.870
So it's all shot up.

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:08.770
So we've become a
world, if you will,

00:14:08.770 --> 00:14:10.359
of global economic migrants.

00:14:10.359 --> 00:14:12.400
Everyone is wondering
either from the countryside

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:15.000
in the cities, across
borders, from one city

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.720
to another city in
search of a better life,

00:14:17.720 --> 00:14:19.300
in search of
economic opportunity.

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:20.710
But it continues unabated.

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:23.800
And I will put my money
on this continuing.

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:27.400
Because in a supply and demand
world, rather than a nations

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:29.510
and borders world,
countries actually

00:14:29.510 --> 00:14:31.860
wind up thinking
pragmatically about what

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:35.560
their needs are for
their economies-- what

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:36.830
their demographic needs are.

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:39.069
And the same places that
are talking about putting up

00:14:39.069 --> 00:14:40.610
walls and borders
are the places that

00:14:40.610 --> 00:14:43.210
actually most need immigrants.

00:14:43.210 --> 00:14:45.980
Countries with aging populations
like in Europe and the United

00:14:45.980 --> 00:14:46.860
States.

00:14:46.860 --> 00:14:49.720
So I think that we
need to differentiate

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:51.970
between the short term
populism of politicians

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:54.310
and the long term
realities of a world

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.850
in which connectivity
facilitates migration.

00:14:56.850 --> 00:14:59.780
More passports have visa
free access around the world.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:01.740
Again, there are going
to be more frictions.

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:05.620
We can see that happening
right now with legislation

00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:07.300
that Congress has passed.

00:15:07.300 --> 00:15:09.790
There are more frictions,
yes, for security reasons.

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:12.290
Smart sensible frictions
are not a bad thing.

00:15:12.290 --> 00:15:16.060
They help to prevent everything
from pandemics to terrorists

00:15:16.060 --> 00:15:17.350
from entering a country.

00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:19.770
But by and large,
those frictions

00:15:19.770 --> 00:15:22.960
don't slow the overall
pattern of migration flows.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:25.760
So this is another way of
rendering it and showing

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:29.550
just how many people are
moving around the world

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:33.280
within and across and
amongst the continents.

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:36.090
And it shows you not
only how important it is,

00:15:36.090 --> 00:15:38.690
how systematic it
is demographically,

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:41.000
but how important
it is economically

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.460
in terms of the values
of the remittance flows.

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:45.970
And so there's an enormous
two-way benefit, of course,

00:15:45.970 --> 00:15:47.350
to global migration.

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:50.330
Some economists
argue that you could

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:54.040
double world GDP by listing
migration restrictions.

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:56.786
I think that may
not be too far off.

00:15:56.786 --> 00:15:59.160
I'm going to jump ahead a
little bit because I don't want

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:01.535
to take too long, but I want
to show you some of the maps

00:16:01.535 --> 00:16:05.580
that I think are more accurate
representations of how humanity

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:06.630
is organized.

00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:07.730
And this is one of them.

00:16:07.730 --> 00:16:09.920
What's captured on this
map and not captured

00:16:09.920 --> 00:16:12.350
on any conventional map
that hangs on your walls

00:16:12.350 --> 00:16:13.490
is quite a few things.

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:15.280
First of all, you can
actually see people.

00:16:15.280 --> 00:16:18.290
You don't just see artificial
states and boundaries.

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:20.590
What you see is every single
human being on the world

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:21.720
is on this map.

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:25.800
And yellow being the
most dense geographies.

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:29.960
Then, most importantly,
you see the dotted ovals,

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:33.480
which show you the largest
or most economically

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:36.010
significant urban clusters.

00:16:36.010 --> 00:16:37.730
So you see Silicon Valley there.

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:40.720
And of course this
northeastern megalopolis,

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:42.410
where we're the
midway point here

00:16:42.410 --> 00:16:45.070
in New York between
Boston and Washington.

00:16:45.070 --> 00:16:49.050
You can see clusters like
Sao Paulo or Johannesburg,

00:16:49.050 --> 00:16:51.680
South Africa, Lagos,
Nigeria, and so on and so on.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:55.600
And you can also see just
how they are not only

00:16:55.600 --> 00:16:58.840
the most important anchors
of their national economies,

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:01.640
but even entire regional
economies depend

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:03.460
on just a couple of cities.

00:17:03.460 --> 00:17:07.280
So shown a different way,
this is the projection

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:09.660
until the year 2030.

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:12.990
I looked at the data of
projections by the World Bank,

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:15.619
by the United Nations-- all
sorts of organizations--

00:17:15.619 --> 00:17:18.530
about what are the
main mega cities that

00:17:18.530 --> 00:17:21.720
are emerging either today or
in the next 10 to 15 years?

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:23.849
If you want to be
megacity in the year 2030,

00:17:23.849 --> 00:17:26.160
you would actually already
have to be well on your way

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:26.819
today, right?

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:28.980
So we can say with
some certainty

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:31.230
that this is not only
the map of today,

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:33.030
this is also the map of 2030.

00:17:33.030 --> 00:17:35.590
I don't think in the
year 2030 I would

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:38.710
need a different
PowerPoint slide than this.

00:17:38.710 --> 00:17:41.660
Because this is
already the areas

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:46.069
with the most dense
concentrations of populations

00:17:46.069 --> 00:17:46.610
in the world.

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:49.760
And these cities are
so significant, again,

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:51.980
economically that
I think if you want

00:17:51.980 --> 00:17:55.122
to understand the map of the
world in the 21st century,

00:17:55.122 --> 00:17:56.580
you're much better
off just looking

00:17:56.580 --> 00:17:59.270
at these cities and the
connections between them

00:17:59.270 --> 00:18:01.430
to understand how the
world really operates.

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:04.860
So I coin this term
connectography.

00:18:04.860 --> 00:18:07.210
By the way, no one says this
with more beautiful accent

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:09.630
than you, Yasmin.

00:18:09.630 --> 00:18:11.730
But the other term
that I come up

00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:13.820
with in this book
is diplomacity--

00:18:13.820 --> 00:18:16.310
the diplomacy among
cities is ultimately

00:18:16.310 --> 00:18:19.570
more revealing about
how the world operates.

00:18:19.570 --> 00:18:21.980
Think about mergers
between stock exchanges,

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:24.790
think about nonstop
flights connecting

00:18:24.790 --> 00:18:26.230
any two cities in the world.

00:18:26.230 --> 00:18:28.750
It seems like Emirates
Airlines wants

00:18:28.750 --> 00:18:31.860
you to be able to fly
around the world nonstop.

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:33.560
They're flying now
to Panama City,

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:36.660
to Auckland, New Zealand,
pretty soon the Sydney.

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:39.300
So this point-to-point travel.

00:18:39.300 --> 00:18:42.880
Obviously, the data networks and
internet cables linking cities

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:45.910
and so on and so on, you
find that the relationships

00:18:45.910 --> 00:18:48.580
among cities tell you
almost most of what

00:18:48.580 --> 00:18:51.450
you need to know, in a way,
about the day-to-day reality

00:18:51.450 --> 00:18:53.960
certainly of the world
economy and world society.

00:18:53.960 --> 00:18:56.600
So how did places get there?

00:18:56.600 --> 00:19:02.540
We often think of economic
growth as just an accident

00:19:02.540 --> 00:19:06.117
or a byproduct of demographic
expansion, but in fact,

00:19:06.117 --> 00:19:07.700
over the last 50
years, what countries

00:19:07.700 --> 00:19:10.500
have started to do is to
strategically urbanize,

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:12.380
not just accidentally urbanize.

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:15.080
And they do so by creating
these special economic zones.

00:19:15.080 --> 00:19:17.580
So what I've been tracking
is how in the last 50 years

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:19.930
we've grown from a world
of the three or four

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:23.630
or five experimental special
economic zones like Mauritius

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:27.270
or the Dominican
Republic or factory

00:19:27.270 --> 00:19:29.640
towns and industrial
parks and clusters

00:19:29.640 --> 00:19:32.560
within them-- and of course
Shenzhen in southern China.

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:36.030
Now you have 4,000 of them.

00:19:36.030 --> 00:19:38.290
So how did Vietnam
get to be Vietnam?

00:19:38.290 --> 00:19:41.950
How did Vietnam go from
being a country that

00:19:41.950 --> 00:19:46.590
was so heavily bombarded and
fought against the United

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:49.230
States in the Vietnam War
to what it is today, which

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:51.770
is considered the next China
industrial powerhouse--

00:19:51.770 --> 00:19:54.670
the Germany of East Asia?

00:19:54.670 --> 00:19:55.510
How did that happen?

00:19:55.510 --> 00:19:58.860
Well, it happened because
they copied the China model.

00:19:58.860 --> 00:20:00.534
They designated
dozens or hundreds

00:20:00.534 --> 00:20:02.700
of these industrial parks
in special economic zones.

00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:05.180
They started attracting
investment and supply chains

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:06.360
and technology.

00:20:06.360 --> 00:20:08.580
They started moving workers
there and training them

00:20:08.580 --> 00:20:11.280
and ramping up their exports.

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:12.870
That's how they
did it, and that's

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:16.100
what country after country is
doing around the world today.

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:18.000
And I like I said,
there are 4,000

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:19.649
such special economic zones.

00:20:19.649 --> 00:20:21.940
So they're not on our maps,
which is another reason why

00:20:21.940 --> 00:20:23.119
our maps suck.

00:20:23.119 --> 00:20:24.577
So I have a line
in this book where

00:20:24.577 --> 00:20:27.180
I say I've spent the last five
years going to places that

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:29.910
apparently don't exist because
I don't know why they're not

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:32.800
on our maps, but the
locus of economic activity

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:35.020
in most of the world's
emerging economies

00:20:35.020 --> 00:20:38.480
are these cities and special
economic zones that don't even

00:20:38.480 --> 00:20:39.500
make it onto the maps.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:40.970
And yet, they really should.

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:43.210
So what I've done
is to insert them

00:20:43.210 --> 00:20:45.550
visually in a number
of maps in the book.

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:48.320
Entire countries are
reorganizing themselves

00:20:48.320 --> 00:20:54.730
around urban clusters, and even
the most ancient civilizations

00:20:54.730 --> 00:20:56.220
in the world, such
as China, that

00:20:56.220 --> 00:21:00.140
have millennia of unique
cultural and provincial and

00:21:00.140 --> 00:21:02.480
linguistic histories are
saying, wait a minute.

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:05.070
In order to be viable and
competitive economically,

00:21:05.070 --> 00:21:07.480
we have to not
just have this kind

00:21:07.480 --> 00:21:12.440
of historical,
cultural geography.

00:21:12.440 --> 00:21:15.340
But instead, we need to have
a strategic urban geography

00:21:15.340 --> 00:21:19.540
of highly populous, dense,
economically-productive,

00:21:19.540 --> 00:21:22.120
and connected urban zones.

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:25.860
So in the New York
Times this weekend,

00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:28.350
there was a two page map
that I worked with them

00:21:28.350 --> 00:21:30.770
to produce that talked about
how America should do this.

00:21:30.770 --> 00:21:34.200
The United States should
literally reorganize itself

00:21:34.200 --> 00:21:39.310
around seven or eight
mega-regions that

00:21:39.310 --> 00:21:44.450
have similar economic profiles
around the white zones, which

00:21:44.450 --> 00:21:46.940
are the urban hubs
that either are

00:21:46.940 --> 00:21:49.440
between or in the heart
of those regions that

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.080
are their financial
and demographic

00:21:52.080 --> 00:21:53.940
and infrastructural centers.

00:21:53.940 --> 00:21:57.910
And then, the lighter lines are
the high-speed railway networks

00:21:57.910 --> 00:21:59.990
that would connect
those cities together.

00:21:59.990 --> 00:22:02.790
So you would move from the
United States of America

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:05.650
towards the United
city-states of America.

00:22:05.650 --> 00:22:07.940
Now, let's bear in
mind that I actually

00:22:07.940 --> 00:22:11.130
softened the argument for fear
of the backlash against it,

00:22:11.130 --> 00:22:14.750
but the feedback on this has
been so positive that I wish

00:22:14.750 --> 00:22:18.170
I'd gone back and doubled down
on the argument in the op ed

00:22:18.170 --> 00:22:19.630
and said, actually,
the 50 states

00:22:19.630 --> 00:22:21.713
are literally pretty useless
other than for what's

00:22:21.713 --> 00:22:24.290
happening right now, which is
collecting electoral votes.

00:22:24.290 --> 00:22:27.730
But after that, after you've
won this primary or that primary

00:22:27.730 --> 00:22:29.619
and made it into
the White House,

00:22:29.619 --> 00:22:31.410
what does that mean
for the competitiveness

00:22:31.410 --> 00:22:35.040
of the entire country
that you have to govern?

00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:38.080
And it turns out the 50 states
mean absolutely nothing.

00:22:38.080 --> 00:22:39.990
They certainly cause
a lot of friction.

00:22:39.990 --> 00:22:42.530
I've gotten so many emails from
people in the last 48 hours

00:22:42.530 --> 00:22:44.470
saying damn right.

00:22:44.470 --> 00:22:46.370
I live in the tiny
state of Rhode Island,

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:50.470
where we have 30, 40
counties and we duplicate

00:22:50.470 --> 00:22:52.630
our education and our
sanitation and all

00:22:52.630 --> 00:22:54.180
these layers of bureaucracy.

00:22:54.180 --> 00:22:56.790
And all that does is waste
money on politics rather than

00:22:56.790 --> 00:23:00.060
on productive,
commercial activity.

00:23:00.060 --> 00:23:01.860
So I feel even more
strongly about this

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:06.030
than I did four days ago
before this was published.

00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:08.210
There's a lot more to say
about this, not only here

00:23:08.210 --> 00:23:09.510
but also in the book.

00:23:09.510 --> 00:23:11.270
So more of the re-mapping.

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:14.420
I want to point out the entire
world is remapping itself.

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:18.650
Region after region is building
infrastructure across borders

00:23:18.650 --> 00:23:21.060
such that if you
were to map that, you

00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:24.120
would get a totally different
appreciation for how

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:25.640
entire continents operate.

00:23:25.640 --> 00:23:28.850
This is my map of the
North American Union

00:23:28.850 --> 00:23:32.050
in which you can see that the
United States gets electricity

00:23:32.050 --> 00:23:32.710
from Canada.

00:23:32.710 --> 00:23:35.610
There's all of these railways
and energy and pipelines

00:23:35.610 --> 00:23:38.580
and freight railways between
Canada and the United States.

00:23:38.580 --> 00:23:41.680
The US is investing heavily
in the Mexican energy system.

00:23:41.680 --> 00:23:46.330
It's doing joint production
of automobiles in Mexico.

00:23:46.330 --> 00:23:49.199
San Diego and Tijuana now
share an airport terminal.

00:23:49.199 --> 00:23:50.740
All of these things--
and eventually,

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:52.156
the United States
is going to need

00:23:52.156 --> 00:23:53.630
more and more Canadian water.

00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:58.790
The Canadians don't really
love this idea-- there's one.

00:23:58.790 --> 00:23:59.750
The token Canadian.

00:24:02.620 --> 00:24:03.982
Oh, two.

00:24:03.982 --> 00:24:05.690
I'd say, statistically,
it's about right.

00:24:08.770 --> 00:24:12.580
The point is that in
a world-- actually,

