building more connectivity

00:24:41.550 --> 00:24:43.490
so that African
countries can more

00:24:43.490 --> 00:24:45.650
seamlessly export their
goods together and scale

00:24:45.650 --> 00:24:46.970
their economies.

00:24:46.970 --> 00:24:48.880
That, I think, is a
very important pathway

00:24:48.880 --> 00:24:52.450
out of thinking about the
future of the Middle East.

00:24:52.450 --> 00:24:54.770
You have the
spectacular collapse

00:24:54.770 --> 00:24:56.410
of the modern Arab state.

00:24:56.410 --> 00:24:58.190
It didn't last very long.

00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:01.820
And the post-colonial
decay of countries

00:25:01.820 --> 00:25:04.850
that were born out of the French
and British empire in the 1940s

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:07.320
has been an obsession
of mine for a long time.

00:25:07.320 --> 00:25:10.400
It traces its way
through all of my books.

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:13.060
And this is finally a time where
I say, OK, so what comes next?

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:15.570
What do you do in
the post-Arab Spring?

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:18.746
You can't really pretend that
Iraq exist or will exist again.

00:25:18.746 --> 00:25:20.120
You can't really
pretend the same

00:25:20.120 --> 00:25:22.820
for Syria or for any
number of other countries.

00:25:22.820 --> 00:25:25.540
But let's go back to
the fact that the cities

00:25:25.540 --> 00:25:27.540
of the Mesopotamian
region in the Middle East

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:29.890
are the oldest cities
that we have in the world.

00:25:29.890 --> 00:25:31.720
And they're continuously
functioning,

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:33.960
and they have that relative
degree of stability

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:35.280
that states don't have.

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:38.050
So I see the Middle East is
capable of-- it certainly

00:25:38.050 --> 00:25:41.410
has the money to do so--
capable of building itself

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:46.110
into an connected,
inter-urban sort of system.

00:25:46.110 --> 00:25:49.100
And I hope that that's where
the investment from the outside

00:25:49.100 --> 00:25:52.190
and from within the
Arab world can go.

00:25:52.190 --> 00:25:54.780
So the geopolitics we can
talk about with Yasmin

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:57.424
because that's a
specialty of hers as well.

00:25:57.424 --> 00:25:58.590
This is one of my favorites.

00:25:58.590 --> 00:26:00.173
I'm going to show
you one or two more.

00:26:00.173 --> 00:26:05.210
This is five billion people or
so, give or take, on this map.

00:26:05.210 --> 00:26:09.630
Most of the world's
population is in Eurasia.

00:26:09.630 --> 00:26:11.270
Just India and
China alone, to say

00:26:11.270 --> 00:26:13.730
nothing of Southeast
Asia and the Middle East

00:26:13.730 --> 00:26:15.280
and so forth--
you've got literally

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:17.570
almost five billion people.

00:26:17.570 --> 00:26:21.130
So eastern Eurasia is
a world unto itself.

00:26:21.130 --> 00:26:25.480
And you certainly heard in 2015
about the Asia Infrastructure

00:26:25.480 --> 00:26:27.800
and Investment Bank, which
is going to be putting up

00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:33.000
$150 billion and more with
many countries participating

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.320
to build infrastructure
across Eurasia.

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:39.570
And in fact, that process
already began 25 years ago.

00:26:39.570 --> 00:26:42.715
The Soviet Union collapsed
in the early 1990s,

00:26:42.715 --> 00:26:46.200
and ever since then, China has
begun this process of building

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:49.670
railways, highways,
pipelines, electricity

00:26:49.670 --> 00:26:53.420
grids, water canals, and so
forth to link up Eurasia.

00:26:53.420 --> 00:26:54.970
Now, why is it doing that?

00:26:54.970 --> 00:26:58.170
Well, China has more neighbors
than any country in the world.

00:26:58.170 --> 00:26:59.920
China has 14 neighbors.

00:26:59.920 --> 00:27:02.220
It doesn't want to fight
a war with any of them.

00:27:02.220 --> 00:27:04.110
In fact, every
neighbor of China is

00:27:04.110 --> 00:27:06.970
suspicious of China
for good reason.

00:27:06.970 --> 00:27:09.920
So what China
does-- I like to use

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:12.650
this analogy from the
construction industry--

00:27:12.650 --> 00:27:15.970
it's going to build, own,
and operate its neighbors.

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:17.882
What do contractors do?

00:27:17.882 --> 00:27:19.340
They build, they
own, they operate.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:21.214
So China isn't going to
invade its neighbors,

00:27:21.214 --> 00:27:23.979
because that will obviously
heighten tensions even further.

00:27:23.979 --> 00:27:26.020
But it's just going to
build its way across them.

00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:29.200
And it's going to do so to
achieve the supply chain world.

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:31.830
It's going to smooth the
inflow of commodities

00:27:31.830 --> 00:27:33.580
and raw materials that
it needs, and it's

00:27:33.580 --> 00:27:36.845
going to smooth the outflow--
the export-- of the electronics

00:27:36.845 --> 00:27:38.970
and other goods that
it manufactures.

00:27:38.970 --> 00:27:41.870
And to do so, its
infrastructurally

00:27:41.870 --> 00:27:43.880
reorganizing all of Eurasia.

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:45.830
So the lives of
five billion people

00:27:45.830 --> 00:27:48.950
are being touched by this
Chinese activity that

00:27:48.950 --> 00:27:53.390
began 25 years ago and is
accelerating every single year.

00:27:53.390 --> 00:27:57.455
So I think of AIIB-- the Asian
Infrastructure and Investment

00:27:57.455 --> 00:28:00.360
Bank-- I think of it as the
NATO of the 21st century.

00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:01.980
And that's
instructive because we

00:28:01.980 --> 00:28:06.040
think of security as being the
world's paramount public good.

00:28:06.040 --> 00:28:08.190
The United States is the
foremost provider of it,

00:28:08.190 --> 00:28:09.800
especially since World War II.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:11.810
But along comes China
and says, well, there's

00:28:11.810 --> 00:28:14.630
another global public good
as important as security.

00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:15.505
It is infrastructure.

00:28:15.505 --> 00:28:17.580
It is connectivity.

00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:21.000
Every country seems to want
it because 60 or 70 countries

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:24.777
lined up to join this bank as
soon as it was established.

00:28:24.777 --> 00:28:26.610
And China is going to
be the world's largest

00:28:26.610 --> 00:28:27.930
provider of this.

00:28:27.930 --> 00:28:31.025
So the NATO of the 21st
century is the AIIB,

00:28:31.025 --> 00:28:34.530
and it's a world in which
people crave and need

00:28:34.530 --> 00:28:37.490
that connectivity and
infrastructure as much

00:28:37.490 --> 00:28:39.480
as they want security.

00:28:39.480 --> 00:28:41.360
So another couple of maps.

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:42.469
Aha, this one.

00:28:42.469 --> 00:28:44.760
This is another one that
Canadians may not like so much

00:28:44.760 --> 00:28:46.620
