00:28:46.620 --> 00:28:51.230
If our climate change
projections are correct--

00:28:51.230 --> 00:28:53.870
and this is a map that was
made by the British journal

00:28:53.870 --> 00:28:56.650
the New Scientist-- they said
if the world temperatures rise

00:28:56.650 --> 00:28:59.970
four degrees Celsius
above the 1990 baseline

00:28:59.970 --> 00:29:04.990
that the IPCC uses, where will
the world's food production be?

00:29:04.990 --> 00:29:10.090
And so what you find if their
extrapolation is correct

00:29:10.090 --> 00:29:12.130
and the impact that
this temperature rise

00:29:12.130 --> 00:29:14.990
is going to have in terms
of wiping out the food

00:29:14.990 --> 00:29:17.770
production in what our today
some of the world's most

00:29:17.770 --> 00:29:20.240
significant bread baskets--
the world's largest food

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:24.160
producers are the United
States, Brazil, India, China,

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:26.660
Australia, and a
couple other countries.

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:30.160
So notice those countries
are all now pasty brown.

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:32.660
They've all been
desertified, if you will.

00:29:32.660 --> 00:29:34.450
And a food production
will happen

00:29:34.450 --> 00:29:38.780
in areas that have traditionally
been tundra and Arctic, which

00:29:38.780 --> 00:29:40.357
is to say Canada and Russia.

00:29:40.357 --> 00:29:41.940
But what are the two
largest countries

00:29:41.940 --> 00:29:44.349
in the world and two of the
most depopulated countries

00:29:44.349 --> 00:29:44.890
in the world?

00:29:44.890 --> 00:29:46.200
Russia and Canada.

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:48.080
So here you have
a situation where

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:52.170
the geography of the world's
population today, which

00:29:52.170 --> 00:29:54.990
is almost everyone south
of the Arctic Circle--

00:29:54.990 --> 00:29:56.545
66 degrees north latitude.

00:29:56.545 --> 00:30:01.060
Do you know how many people live
north of the Arctic Circle ring

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:02.440
today?

00:30:02.440 --> 00:30:04.590
It's less than the
population of Manhattan.

00:30:04.590 --> 00:30:07.230
It's less than
four million people

00:30:07.230 --> 00:30:09.270
who live in the
entire Arctic Circle.

00:30:09.270 --> 00:30:12.530
And yet, we're heading to a
world where most of the food

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:14.430
is supposedly going to
be coming from there.

00:30:14.430 --> 00:30:17.060
That requires us to think pretty
differently about the world

00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:18.610
than just nations and borders.

00:30:18.610 --> 00:30:20.540
We have to think
about food supply

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:24.000
chains and mass migrations
and new kinds of settlements.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.910
And this is just the final nail
in the coffin in the argument.

00:30:26.910 --> 00:30:29.980
As if the internet and
connectivity and infrastructure

00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:32.840
and economies and
migration weren't enough

00:30:32.840 --> 00:30:35.610
cause to believe that the
world is reorganizing itself,

00:30:35.610 --> 00:30:38.810
here's the icing on the cake.

00:30:38.810 --> 00:30:39.940
We will just have to.

00:30:39.940 --> 00:30:43.390
And this is even absent
rising sea levels

00:30:43.390 --> 00:30:47.680
and coastal inundations and
potential tsunamis having

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:50.600
a devastating impact on the
world's coastal megacities,

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:52.530
particularly in Asia.

00:30:52.530 --> 00:30:55.881
So we could be in for, obviously
a stormy and turbulent time--

00:30:55.881 --> 00:30:57.130
people always talk about that.

00:30:57.130 --> 00:30:59.520
But think about the
consequences for what

00:30:59.520 --> 00:31:01.790
we do the next day and the
next day and the next day.

00:31:01.790 --> 00:31:03.540
And it's going to
require rethinking

00:31:03.540 --> 00:31:04.930
how we organize ourselves.

00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:07.580
And that's what
this is all about.

