There've been a lot
of media reports that

00:36:13.170 --> 00:36:14.466
call them ghost towns.

00:36:14.466 --> 00:36:16.340
But then you go back
after four or five years

00:36:16.340 --> 00:36:18.756
and they're starting to fill
up because people are looking

00:36:18.756 --> 00:36:21.120
to move out of places
that have been wiped out

00:36:21.120 --> 00:36:24.366
as the manufacturing sector has
collapsed, wages have risen.

00:36:24.366 --> 00:36:25.990
So they're moving
into these new towns.

00:36:25.990 --> 00:36:30.460
And a city, to remain
economically viable in terms

00:36:30.460 --> 00:36:33.670
of its services sector or
having a resilient services

00:36:33.670 --> 00:36:37.590
economy, versus being dependent
on manufacturing exports that

00:36:37.590 --> 00:36:40.560
are highly volatile, you need
to have at least three to four

00:36:40.560 --> 00:36:43.990
million people various
research suggests.

00:36:43.990 --> 00:36:45.990
So the problem with
many American cities

00:36:45.990 --> 00:36:48.270
is that their populations
are below a million people.

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:49.190
So you take Detroit.

00:36:49.190 --> 00:36:52.420
Detroit's population fell
to below a million people,

00:36:52.420 --> 00:36:56.900
and it lacked that internally
resilient services economy

00:36:56.900 --> 00:37:01.730
that would allow it to sustain
itself beyond export oriented

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:03.610
automobile industry.

00:37:03.610 --> 00:37:07.450
So we need to re-aggregate
our cities in a way

00:37:07.450 --> 00:37:12.440
that they can be
internally viable.

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:14.742
And so the way I
describe Detroit's future

00:37:14.742 --> 00:37:16.700
in this New York Time's
piece is that it should

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:20.650
be seen as the midway point
on a Chicago-Toronto corridor

00:37:20.650 --> 00:37:22.900
within this broader
North American Union.

00:37:22.900 --> 00:37:26.560
That's just not the way
Congresspeople think.

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:30.177
I mean, we are a long, long
way from our Congress, which

00:37:30.177 --> 00:37:31.760
of course everything
is about fighting

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:35.970
for fiscal and budgetary
scraps to go into your state,

00:37:35.970 --> 00:37:38.230
not caring about whether
or not that infrastructure

00:37:38.230 --> 00:37:41.830
or connectivity stretches across
one state boundary to another

00:37:41.830 --> 00:37:43.650
so that you can
mutually benefit.

00:37:43.650 --> 00:37:46.160
We are down here when it
comes to the sophistication

00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:48.460
of our political
logic and stretching

00:37:48.460 --> 00:37:49.850
beyond our state boundaries.

00:37:49.850 --> 00:37:52.830
Meanwhile, what I'm proposing
is it makes total sense.

00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:54.010
Just look at a map.

00:37:54.010 --> 00:37:56.430
Chicago, Toronto,
Detroit in the middle,

00:37:56.430 --> 00:37:58.900
you should be having a
trade and industry corridor.

00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:00.650
That's an export
powerhouse taking

00:38:00.650 --> 00:38:04.390
advantage of Arctic shipping
routes through Hudson Bay.

00:38:04.390 --> 00:38:08.340
In Washington, they can't
even find Hudson Bay on a map

00:38:08.340 --> 00:38:10.140
and I wish I weren't
exaggerating,

00:38:10.140 --> 00:38:12.950
but that's where we need to be.

00:38:12.950 --> 00:38:16.360
An even second tier Chinese
cities you can go to,

00:38:16.360 --> 00:38:18.900
they've all got their
own economic master

00:38:18.900 --> 00:38:20.770
plans and strategies--
what industries

00:38:20.770 --> 00:38:23.880
they want to attract, what
companies are they targeting,

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:25.930
what supply chains do
they want to be part of.

00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:28.646
All of these things they're
thinking way, way, way ahead.

00:38:28.646 --> 00:38:30.020
Now, there are a
number of cities

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.880
that are starting to do
this like Columbus, Ohio,

00:38:32.880 --> 00:38:35.490
and Salt Lake City and
the Brookings Institution

00:38:35.490 --> 00:38:39.120
as a whole department
that consults on this.

00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:41.740
It's starting, but that doesn't
mean it's going to succeed.

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:43.800
Just like in China or
other places in the world,

00:38:43.800 --> 00:38:46.580
cities get wiped out.

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:47.970
Industries rise and fall.

00:38:47.970 --> 00:38:49.250
People have to move.

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:51.950
The beautiful thing I would
say about America-- the virtue,

00:38:51.950 --> 00:38:54.990
the luck, the manifest destiny,
whatever you want to call it--

00:38:54.990 --> 00:38:59.120
is that America is so large,
so devolved, so federalized, so

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:03.200
distributed, has so many
large population centers

00:39:03.200 --> 00:39:07.752
that people can re-sort when you
have these economic convulsions

00:39:07.752 --> 00:39:08.710
like we've been having.

00:39:08.710 --> 00:39:10.380
And it's one of the
things that people

00:39:10.380 --> 00:39:12.530
have to take advantage of.

00:39:12.530 --> 00:39:14.080
The history of
American migration

00:39:14.080 --> 00:39:17.720
is searching for opportunity
in new geographies,

00:39:17.720 --> 00:39:20.900
and so I think that great
re-sorting as some economists

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:22.560
and sociologists
call it is actually

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:23.980
underway today in America.

00:39:23.980 --> 00:39:28.889
It may seem tragic and painful
to see the lack of opportunity

00:39:28.889 --> 00:39:30.680
in many areas and the
fact that people just

00:39:30.680 --> 00:39:32.960
have to just get up and go.

00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:35.030
But that's actually part
of American history,

00:39:35.030 --> 00:39:36.690
and think about
all the countries

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:38.680
where you don't have
that possibility, where

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:41.260
the entire economy centers
around one city and nothing

00:39:41.260 --> 00:39:41.760
else.

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:44.302
And if that city fails,
if that economy fails,

00:39:44.302 --> 00:39:46.010
if the one industry
that drives it fails,

00:39:46.010 --> 00:39:47.219
the whole country is screwed.

00:39:47.219 --> 00:39:48.885
That's never going
to happen to America.

00:39:48.885 --> 00:39:50.840
And America is lucky,
but it should actually

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:54.260
build the infrastructure to
make it more possible for people

00:39:54.260 --> 00:39:57.670
to make those moves today that
are necessary to revitalize

00:39:57.670 --> 00:40:00.040
society and the economy.

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:03.375
YASMIN: You spoke about
cities being the only thing

00:40:03.375 --> 00:40:05.440
that you can see from
space and the thing

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:08.090
that we've had for 5,000
years as well-- the nation

00:40:08.090 --> 00:40:12.950
states in the Westphalian
system are 200 years old.

00:40:12.950 --> 00:40:17.310
Let's imagine that the
megacity model in China

00:40:17.310 --> 00:40:20.300
and exporting it and
say that Congress

00:40:20.300 --> 00:40:24.650
adopts your prescriptions in
your New York Times op ed,

00:40:24.650 --> 00:40:28.410
what does this mean
for the nation state

00:40:28.410 --> 00:40:30.620
and also for national identity?

00:40:30.620 --> 00:40:35.160
Many Americans,
Europeans, Canadians

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:38.010
enjoy their sense of
national identity.

00:40:38.010 --> 00:40:41.430
What happens when
the city takes over

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:44.180
as the atom and
the building block?

00:40:44.180 --> 00:40:47.050
PARAG KHANNA: So
history is cumulative,

00:40:47.050 --> 00:40:49.700
it's not substitutive.

00:40:49.700 --> 00:40:52.050
Nothing that I've
said at any point

00:40:52.050 --> 00:40:56.890
should suggest that nations
and states and boundaries

00:40:56.890 --> 00:40:59.440
and national
governments disappear.

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:01.773
We're always going to live
in some country or the other.

00:41:01.773 --> 00:41:04.320
The entire world's
physical geography

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:06.274
is claimed by sovereign states.

00:41:06.274 --> 00:41:07.940
In fact, there are
many geographies that

00:41:07.940 --> 00:41:09.390
are claimed by multiple states.

00:41:09.390 --> 00:41:11.790
You will always be standing
on the territory that

00:41:11.790 --> 00:41:14.630
belongs to or is claimed
by a sovereign government.

00:41:14.630 --> 00:41:16.320
I've got no problem with that.

00:41:16.320 --> 00:41:17.690
But history is additive.

00:41:17.690 --> 00:41:19.510
It's the cities from
5,000 years ago,

00:41:19.510 --> 00:41:21.380
it's the empires
that have existed

00:41:21.380 --> 00:41:23.370
for thousands of years--
America is an empire.

00:41:23.370 --> 00:41:24.887
Europe has empires.

00:41:24.887 --> 00:41:26.220
The European Union is an empire.

00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:27.480
China is an empire.

00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:28.840
India is an empire.

00:41:28.840 --> 00:41:31.050
And then you have the
states that are now

00:41:31.050 --> 00:41:32.790
another layer on top of that.

00:41:32.790 --> 00:41:35.050
So you have sovereignty,
you have enlightenment,

00:41:35.050 --> 00:41:37.030
you have technology,
you have capitalism,

00:41:37.030 --> 00:41:39.040
you have infrastructure--
all these things just

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:40.700
keep on and on layering.

00:41:40.700 --> 00:41:43.290
So the city doesn't
replace the country anymore

00:41:43.290 --> 00:41:45.680
than the country ever
replaced the city.

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:49.330
These things just make the
world more complicated.

00:41:49.330 --> 00:41:52.790
And that complexity applies
to all of us in our identity

00:41:52.790 --> 00:41:53.590
as well.

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:56.596
If you were never able
to connect to anyone

00:41:56.596 --> 00:41:57.970
outside your
national boundaries,

00:41:57.970 --> 00:42:00.660
if you had no access to
information, if you couldn't

00:42:00.660 --> 00:42:02.790
leave the country in
which you were born,

00:42:02.790 --> 00:42:06.980
you would have a relatively
limited selection

00:42:06.980 --> 00:42:09.520
of identities to choose from--
that which is prescribed

00:42:09.520 --> 00:42:11.290
by the king, that
which is prescribed

00:42:11.290 --> 00:42:13.460
by the pope, whatever
the case may be.

00:42:13.460 --> 00:42:15.260
That's not the case anymore.

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:17.740
And so what I find,
especially in a world that

00:42:17.740 --> 00:42:21.200
is very young-- I mean 40%,
50% of the world's population

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:24.862
is young and youthful, and
a large share of the world's

00:42:24.862 --> 00:42:25.820
population is also old.

00:42:25.820 --> 00:42:28.730
But when I travel around and
I talk to young people, what

00:42:28.730 --> 00:42:32.220
I find is not a sense
that national identity

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:35.150
is the only identity
that matters to them.

00:42:35.150 --> 00:42:37.480
It's not something you
have to reject in order

00:42:37.480 --> 00:42:41.440
to appreciate and
absorb and embrace

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:42.700
the multitude of identities.

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:44.880
So I talk in this
book about civicism,

00:42:44.880 --> 00:42:48.225
which is a new-ish term
coined by a friend of mine,

00:42:48.225 --> 00:42:51.250
in which he says the pride
and loyalty in a city.

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:53.050
Of course, if you're
New Yorker like I am,

00:42:53.050 --> 00:42:56.224
you're a New Yorker first.

00:42:56.224 --> 00:42:58.390
YASMIN: How old were you
when you moved to New York?

00:42:58.390 --> 00:43:00.429
PARAG KHANNA: I was six.

00:43:00.429 --> 00:43:02.345
YASMIN: So you get to
say you're a New Yorker?

00:43:02.345 --> 00:43:02.600
PARAG KHANNA: Yeah.

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:05.010
YASMIN: No one disputes
that your a New Yorker.

00:43:05.010 --> 00:43:06.660
PARAG KHANNA: They dare not.

00:43:06.660 --> 00:43:08.409
YASMIN: Because I
wonder how long it would

00:43:08.409 --> 00:43:10.360
take me to be a New Yorker.

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:12.600
PARAG KHANNA: Let me just
say something about this.

00:43:12.600 --> 00:43:16.740
This a city-- right now in
Albany and elsewhere, they're

00:43:16.740 --> 00:43:18.730
actually discussing
whether or not

00:43:18.730 --> 00:43:21.460
to give migrants and
non-citizens voting

00:43:21.460 --> 00:43:24.590
rights in municipal elections.

00:43:24.590 --> 00:43:27.450
So vote for mayor of New
York or in city council

00:43:27.450 --> 00:43:28.770
ballots and referendum.

00:43:28.770 --> 00:43:30.190
I think that's awesome.

00:43:30.190 --> 00:43:33.009
Obviously, you're a New
Yorker if you're able to vote.

00:43:33.009 --> 00:43:35.050
You could be someone who
is not even naturalized.

00:43:35.050 --> 00:43:37.690
You could be an illegal
alien who is just

00:43:37.690 --> 00:43:40.101
in some way given
some identity card

00:43:40.101 --> 00:43:41.600
and you might be
able to participate

00:43:41.600 --> 00:43:43.900
in the politics of the state.

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:47.165
You will not be voting for
president for a very long time,

00:43:47.165 --> 00:43:49.540
but the politics of the city,
you're going to be part of.

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:50.623
I think that's incredible.

00:43:50.623 --> 00:43:54.600
Only cities like
Rotterdam and Toronto

00:43:54.600 --> 00:43:57.062
and Hamburg and New
York and other places

00:43:57.062 --> 00:43:59.020
are actually starting to
do that kind of thing,

00:43:59.020 --> 00:44:01.200
because they say--
like ancient Athens,

00:44:01.200 --> 00:44:03.430
by the way, just going back
to the history of cities,

00:44:03.430 --> 00:44:07.550
where there any
resident of Athens

00:44:07.550 --> 00:44:10.650
was part of the
polity of Athens.

00:44:10.650 --> 00:44:16.060
And there's nothing so radical
of that coming back today.

00:44:16.060 --> 00:44:18.430
One of the biggest
sections in the book

00:44:18.430 --> 00:44:19.660
is actually about devolution.

00:44:19.660 --> 00:44:24.040
It's about cities and provinces
reclaiming their right

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:24.990
to govern themselves.

00:44:24.990 --> 00:44:26.980
Because that's where
the decisions are made,

00:44:26.980 --> 00:44:29.063
that's where lives are
affected, that's why mayors

00:44:29.063 --> 00:44:30.260
are becoming so powerful.

00:44:30.260 --> 00:44:32.310
That's why when
someone like Bloomberg

00:44:32.310 --> 00:44:34.030
entertains running
for president,

00:44:34.030 --> 00:44:35.860
so many people
take it seriously.

00:44:35.860 --> 00:44:38.160
That's why there are more
president's today-- active,

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:40.310
sitting, serving
presidents today--

00:44:40.310 --> 00:44:43.440
whose last job was
mayor of a big city

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:44.770
than ever before in history.

00:44:44.770 --> 00:44:46.830
Because that's the stepping
stone of proving you actually

00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:47.913
know how to run something.

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:53.565
So civicism is one new kind of
identity beyond your national

00:44:53.565 --> 00:44:55.440
or government identity
or religious identity.

00:44:55.440 --> 00:44:56.898
And then there's
all the identities

00:44:56.898 --> 00:44:58.870
that you acquire
through technology.

00:44:58.870 --> 00:45:04.040
The whole field of social
physics, as it's called,

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:07.020
is about understanding
how people now

00:45:07.020 --> 00:45:08.880
form these cloud communities.

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:10.730
What is your identity
in the cloud?

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:12.880
Not just what's
your avatar's name,

00:45:12.880 --> 00:45:15.790
but how do you feel
about the communities

00:45:15.790 --> 00:45:17.070
that you're part of online.

00:45:17.070 --> 00:45:19.860
People who have a certain cause.

00:45:19.860 --> 00:45:23.290
Arab democracy,
environmentalism, you name it.

00:45:23.290 --> 00:45:26.100
That identity can
be very strong, too.

00:45:26.100 --> 00:45:28.560
And so I don't think that one
has to substitute the other.

00:45:28.560 --> 00:45:30.260
We have to embrace
this complexity.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:33.130
Each of us has many
identities that overlap.

00:45:33.130 --> 00:45:36.760
YASMIN: Yeah, that's
a really nice point.

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:40.140
We have less than 10 minutes,
so I will allow anyone here

00:45:40.140 --> 00:45:41.880
to ask a question now.

00:45:41.880 --> 00:45:43.580
Go ahead.

00:45:43.580 --> 00:45:45.710
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming.

00:45:45.710 --> 00:45:49.960
I have a question-- kind
of a counter-view on this.

00:45:49.960 --> 00:45:54.970
I was thinking that you've
mentioned the maps in terms

00:45:54.970 --> 00:45:57.770
of the city and linking
the cities and the cities

00:45:57.770 --> 00:46:03.550
growing and encompassing
the core of connectivity.

00:46:03.550 --> 00:46:07.950
People and pipelines and
infrastructure and electricity.

00:46:07.950 --> 00:46:11.680
I have a counter-view.

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:15.350
I was thinking in terms of
things are dilluting away

00:46:15.350 --> 00:46:20.790
from cities in the sense that
given that connectivity has

00:46:20.790 --> 00:46:23.850
reached every part, everyone
has a phone now, even

00:46:23.850 --> 00:46:27.800
in India near my small
city where I was born.

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:30.460
And now even
[INAUDIBLE] has a phone.

00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:33.580
He doesn't earn enough,
but he has phone.

00:46:33.580 --> 00:46:38.470
So that means that everyone, if
they wish, can learn and become

00:46:38.470 --> 00:46:41.501
of service-- can
trade their services.

00:46:41.501 --> 00:46:44.000
So that means we don't really
need them to come to services.

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.600
So people should
go away from cities

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:50.380
and start-- I should see
a more uniform lighted

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:53.150
map, which I was kind of
hoping to see in the book.

00:46:56.020 --> 00:46:58.430
Maybe all the bulbs
should light up everywhere

00:46:58.430 --> 00:46:59.865
and then it would
be homogenized.

00:47:03.150 --> 00:47:08.660
The other one I was thinking was
that the four degree centigrade

00:47:08.660 --> 00:47:13.510
increase where most of
South America and India

00:47:13.510 --> 00:47:17.150
was flooded and gone,
that seems to me

00:47:17.150 --> 00:47:19.240
that don't they have
mud in the Himalayas?

00:47:19.240 --> 00:47:21.800
Can't they carry and
put them on the sides

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:25.630
and then they stop the water
from [INAUDIBLE] New York City?

00:47:25.630 --> 00:47:28.950
Keep dumping mud
from Central America

00:47:28.950 --> 00:47:31.300
on the sides of New York City.

00:47:31.300 --> 00:47:35.435
They built Dubai just by
shoving mud into water.

00:47:35.435 --> 00:47:37.810
PARAG KHANNA: It was a little
more complicated than that,

00:47:37.810 --> 00:47:41.279
but that said, land
reclamation is actually

00:47:41.279 --> 00:47:42.570
one of the themes in this book.

00:47:42.570 --> 00:47:44.760
I talk about sand--
the role of sand.

00:47:44.760 --> 00:47:46.700
There's this global
market for sand

00:47:46.700 --> 00:47:50.070
that gets shipped and
towed all over the world

00:47:50.070 --> 00:47:51.540
to build up artificial islands.

00:47:51.540 --> 00:47:53.040
So obviously, you
see this happening

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:55.060
in the South China Sea.

00:47:55.060 --> 00:47:57.240
And I actually say,
think about how much

00:47:57.240 --> 00:48:01.200
the United States spends
on missiles and submarines

00:48:01.200 --> 00:48:06.330
and aircraft carriers and
fighter jets and so forth

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:09.430
and China is using
sand-- silica--

00:48:09.430 --> 00:48:12.630
the most abundant element
in the earth's crust.

00:48:12.630 --> 00:48:14.520
It's free.

00:48:14.520 --> 00:48:16.810
It's now the most powerful
geopolitical weapon.

00:48:16.810 --> 00:48:20.290
China just takes this
sand, dumps it onto rocks,

00:48:20.290 --> 00:48:22.830
and is able to claim new
political sovereignty

00:48:22.830 --> 00:48:24.630
in very sensitive environments.

00:48:24.630 --> 00:48:26.640
So it's a lesson lesson.

00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:29.650
But let me take
your first question.

00:48:29.650 --> 00:48:31.650
I've heard this many times.

00:48:31.650 --> 00:48:35.590
If all it took to convince
people not to move to cities

00:48:35.590 --> 00:48:38.660
is to give them even a
solar-power-charged mobile

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:42.250
phone, then I don't know why
they would move to cities.

00:48:42.250 --> 00:48:44.170
And the truth is you
don't just move to a city

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:46.950
because you really want
to get a Nokia phone.

00:48:46.950 --> 00:48:49.410
You go there for health
care, you go there for jobs,

00:48:49.410 --> 00:48:52.370
you go there for education, you
go there for basic services,

00:48:52.370 --> 00:48:55.290
for income, to send
remittances back,

00:48:55.290 --> 00:49:00.622
to experience modern
life, which are things

00:49:00.622 --> 00:49:01.830
that you're not going to get.

00:49:01.830 --> 00:49:05.160
You're talking
about connectivity

00:49:05.160 --> 00:49:06.970
as if it's just
digital connectivity,

00:49:06.970 --> 00:49:10.370
but the fact is that
the incidence of malaria

00:49:10.370 --> 00:49:15.140
falls drastically if you
have a hardwood or concrete

00:49:15.140 --> 00:49:18.840
floor in your home, which many
billions of people do not have.

00:49:18.840 --> 00:49:20.500
A mobile phone is not the same.

00:49:20.500 --> 00:49:22.680
A mobile phone does
not cure malaria.

00:49:22.680 --> 00:49:26.220
So you will, as I say,
never ever stop people

00:49:26.220 --> 00:49:28.091
from moving to cities.

00:49:28.091 --> 00:49:28.590
Ever.

00:49:28.590 --> 00:49:29.790
There's nothing you can say.

00:49:29.790 --> 00:49:32.480
There's no amount of fiber
cable Google or anyone else

00:49:32.480 --> 00:49:35.520
can lay down to the remote
villages, where of course

00:49:35.520 --> 00:49:38.070
it makes no economic
sense to lay down cables

00:49:38.070 --> 00:49:40.500
to because there's no one there.

00:49:40.500 --> 00:49:43.240
You will never
stop urbanization.

00:49:43.240 --> 00:49:48.440
Only massive, massive
tsunamis drowning the billions

00:49:48.440 --> 00:49:53.370
of people urbanizing
on the Pacific Rim

00:49:53.370 --> 00:49:56.060
is going to stop urbanization.

00:49:56.060 --> 00:49:59.170
So you can't convince people
that just because they

00:49:59.170 --> 00:50:01.170
have a bunch of phones
in rural environments

00:50:01.170 --> 00:50:02.740
that life is better
where they are.

00:50:02.740 --> 00:50:05.140
Because if that were true,
they wouldn't be coming.

00:50:05.140 --> 00:50:07.340
Again, this is a
voluntary process,

00:50:07.340 --> 00:50:10.590
and it is as much or more
so in India than anywhere

00:50:10.590 --> 00:50:11.434
else in the world.

00:50:11.434 --> 00:50:13.350
Of course, the most
rapidly urbanizing country

00:50:13.350 --> 00:50:18.760
on the planet is India, even
though they have exponentially

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:22.326
accelerating mobile
phone penetration.

00:50:22.326 --> 00:50:23.700
AUDIENCE: My
question is slightly

00:50:23.700 --> 00:50:27.010
different from this one.

00:50:27.010 --> 00:50:33.070
Is it right to say that we are
just becoming one civilization?

00:50:33.070 --> 00:50:37.210
If yes, then historically,
civilizations,

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:40.360
they end up collapsing,
and most of the time,

00:50:40.360 --> 00:50:41.960
in a spectacular fashion.

00:50:41.960 --> 00:50:44.664
What makes us different?

00:50:44.664 --> 00:50:46.580
PARAG KHANNA: On the
question of civilization,

00:50:46.580 --> 00:50:48.480
I think it is the
first time when

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:51.800
you can speak of something
like this global network

00:50:51.800 --> 00:50:52.520
civilization.

00:50:52.520 --> 00:50:57.070
It's not a terminology that
we could've used before.

00:50:57.070 --> 00:51:01.530
But civilization in the sense
of those that rise and decline

00:51:01.530 --> 00:51:04.370
as you say in these
spectacular moments

00:51:04.370 --> 00:51:10.610
of collapse, that tends to be
an anthropological, ecological,

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:14.470
and political
pattern with respect

00:51:14.470 --> 00:51:17.780
to specific geographic
cultural civilizations.

00:51:17.780 --> 00:51:20.320
I'm using civilization
in a much looser

00:51:20.320 --> 00:51:24.630
sense of the ability
for mankind to have

00:51:24.630 --> 00:51:29.040
a certain minimal degree of
connectivity amongst its parts

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:32.359
so that you can think of it as
having some kind of a cohesion.

00:51:32.359 --> 00:51:33.900
You never would have
been able to say

00:51:33.900 --> 00:51:37.940
that many generations ago
or certainly centuries

00:51:37.940 --> 00:51:40.810
ago-- the notion that
we are all in this boat

00:51:40.810 --> 00:51:42.150
together, so to speak.

00:51:42.150 --> 00:51:45.660
You didn't hear people exactly
talking like that in the 19th

00:51:45.660 --> 00:51:47.229
and even in the 20th centuries.

00:51:47.229 --> 00:51:49.270
So that's the sense in
which I mean civilization.

00:51:49.270 --> 00:51:50.820
And of course,
again, a lot of it

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:54.240
rests on this physical
connectedness.

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:58.360
You can't influence and
you have much less sympathy

00:51:58.360 --> 00:52:00.300
for that which you
can't touch and feel,

00:52:00.300 --> 00:52:02.320
that which you're
not connected to.

00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:04.080
One of the examples
I give in the book

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:08.160
is the collapse of that
garment factory in Bangladesh

00:52:08.160 --> 00:52:12.940
in the year 2013 where there was
an uproar for months and months

00:52:12.940 --> 00:52:16.160
and years because there
was a Bangladeshi garment

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:18.700
factory making clothing
for Western retailers.

00:52:18.700 --> 00:52:21.780
There was this uproar
saying H&amp;M and Zara

00:52:21.780 --> 00:52:24.190
and these other companies,
what are you doing about this?

00:52:24.190 --> 00:52:26.356
What are you doing about
the plight of those people?

00:52:26.356 --> 00:52:29.310
I mean, can you imagine that
happening even 10 years ago,

00:52:29.310 --> 00:52:29.860
15 years ago?

00:52:29.860 --> 00:52:30.620
No way.

00:52:30.620 --> 00:52:34.460
It's because the supply
chain connects us here

00:52:34.460 --> 00:52:38.120
in rich New York to the
poorest people in the world.

00:52:38.120 --> 00:52:41.200
And so we're able to have some
degree of sympathy or empathy

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:41.700
with them.

00:52:41.700 --> 00:52:44.230
That never, ever, ever
could have been the case.

00:52:44.230 --> 00:52:46.310
And previously, if
it were the case--

00:52:46.310 --> 00:52:48.700
the anti-slavery
movement, for example--

00:52:48.700 --> 00:52:51.770
it was obviously more emotive
and more geographically

00:52:51.770 --> 00:52:52.350
specific.

00:52:52.350 --> 00:52:54.760
But now, you can find
these connections

00:52:54.760 --> 00:52:57.520
through the supply chain
between almost any two people

00:52:57.520 --> 00:52:58.190
in the world.

00:52:58.190 --> 00:53:03.530
And again, that process is
just now getting underway.

00:53:03.530 --> 00:53:04.950
YASMIN: Final closing note.

00:53:04.950 --> 00:53:07.340
I wonder if you could say
something that speaks maybe

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:09.500
to-- you are here at
Google-- maybe to those of us

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:12.210
in the tech sector who think
about connectivity probably

00:53:12.210 --> 00:53:15.260
in only one aspect of the
way that you tackle it

00:53:15.260 --> 00:53:16.010
in this book.

00:53:16.010 --> 00:53:19.420
But the tech sector is
thinking about driver-less cars

00:53:19.420 --> 00:53:26.630
and aerial delivery systems and
AI and automated assistance.

00:53:26.630 --> 00:53:27.910
We're laying down cables.

00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:29.760
We're big on connectivity.

00:53:29.760 --> 00:53:34.710
What would you leave us with as
the promise or the opportunity

00:53:34.710 --> 00:53:38.190
for technology's role
in connectography?

00:53:38.190 --> 00:53:40.140
PARAG KHANNA: So I
point out in the book

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:43.000
that telecom companies,
technology companies,

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:46.100
are infrastructure companies.

00:53:46.100 --> 00:53:48.170
And obviously, Google
is foremost among them

00:53:48.170 --> 00:53:49.740
in terms of literally
contributing

00:53:49.740 --> 00:53:53.310
to this physical, built
infrastructural environment,

00:53:53.310 --> 00:53:54.660
to which I say amen.

00:53:54.660 --> 00:53:57.120
Because we're
desperately lagging

00:53:57.120 --> 00:54:00.680
in that category across the
board of, again, energy,

00:54:00.680 --> 00:54:03.830
transportation,
communications-- what's

00:54:03.830 --> 00:54:06.750
called the infrastructure
stock has been so meager

00:54:06.750 --> 00:54:08.980
for a world of nine
billion people.

00:54:08.980 --> 00:54:12.400
So Google, as well as
very large companies

00:54:12.400 --> 00:54:16.690
like pipeline companies
and railway companies,

00:54:16.690 --> 00:54:18.860
are all agents of connectivity.

00:54:18.860 --> 00:54:21.450
And so they're actually, in a
way, the heroes of this book

00:54:21.450 --> 00:54:24.430
are those that facilitate,
enable, and expand connectivity

00:54:24.430 --> 00:54:27.200
because we have been able
to demonstrate as far

00:54:27.200 --> 00:54:29.310
back as the
Industrial Revolution

00:54:29.310 --> 00:54:33.610
that it is connectivity has
lifted global living standards,

00:54:33.610 --> 00:54:35.710
that has enhanced trade.

00:54:35.710 --> 00:54:38.020
There've been enough Nobel
Prizes given out for this,

00:54:38.020 --> 00:54:41.180
by the way, going back to
like Michael Spence, Angus

00:54:41.180 --> 00:54:46.150
Deaton, Robert Solow-- you
can't disprove the notion

00:54:46.150 --> 00:54:51.290
that connectivity is the agent
of growth in the world economy.

00:54:51.290 --> 00:54:52.750
And it's all forms
of connectivity.

00:54:52.750 --> 00:54:55.320
So even if governments
aren't doing it,

00:54:55.320 --> 00:54:58.052
if the private sector is, I
think that's a fantastic thing.

00:54:58.052 --> 00:55:00.260
And that's not just for
countries, that's for people.

00:55:00.260 --> 00:55:02.930
We can measure now
everything from how

00:55:02.930 --> 00:55:06.210
your labor productivity improves
by being digitally connected.

00:55:06.210 --> 00:55:09.780
We know that in terms of the
workforce around the world.

00:55:09.780 --> 00:55:12.630
So in every way,
connectivity is not

00:55:12.630 --> 00:55:17.610
only something that has this
empirical role in strengthening

00:55:17.610 --> 00:55:19.620
our capacity and
our productivity,

00:55:19.620 --> 00:55:21.750
but it really should
be a human right.

00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:25.357
In this book, connectivity
is presented as a human right

00:55:25.357 --> 00:55:26.190
as much as anything.

00:55:26.190 --> 00:55:28.650
Connectivity and
mobility should really

00:55:28.650 --> 00:55:32.300
be considered two of the
absolute foremost human rights

00:55:32.300 --> 00:55:33.230
in the world.

00:55:33.230 --> 00:55:35.760
And I can't think of any
instance in which it is not

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:38.680
a good thing for a human
being to have an option

00:55:38.680 --> 00:55:40.640
to be more connected
and more mobile.

00:55:40.640 --> 00:55:44.520
And so if you want to talk
about improving mankind's fate,

00:55:44.520 --> 00:55:47.500
you definitely want to extend
that connectivity to everyone

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:48.450
you can.

00:55:48.450 --> 00:55:50.860
So congrats for doing so.

00:55:50.860 --> 00:55:52.780
YASMIN: Wonderful note
to round off the talk.

00:55:52.780 --> 00:55:54.490
Thank you very
much, Parag Khanna.

00:55:54.490 --> 00:55:56.260
PARAG KHANNA: Thank you.

